00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:41.210
There are two lineages,
H1N1 and H3N2,

00:03:41.210 --> 00:03:43.197
that circulate every year.

00:03:43.197 --> 00:03:44.280
And here are some numbers.

00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:49.520
So every year 5% to 30% of
the population gets Infected.

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:51.860
Most of us were probably
infected by the time

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:53.960
we were five years old.

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:56.960
And that first infection
kind of sets the stage

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:59.090
for the rest of your life.

00:03:59.090 --> 00:04:03.624
Your immune system
remembers that first virus,

00:04:03.624 --> 00:04:05.790
and for the rest of your
life kind of responds to it

00:04:05.790 --> 00:04:08.630
every time you're reinfected.

00:04:08.630 --> 00:04:11.240
You get it for about a week
and then you clear the virus.

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:14.430
And it's gone until the
next time you encounter it.

00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:19.010
So just regular old flu every
year accounts for, on average,

00:04:19.010 --> 00:04:23.220
31 million outpatient
visits in the US.

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:26.840
200,000 people end
up in the hospital,

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:31.820
for a total of 3.1
million hospitalized days.

00:04:31.820 --> 00:04:36.410
Total economic burden $87
billion-- that's medical cost,

00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:40.710
work lost, work time
lost, and so forth.

00:04:40.710 --> 00:04:43.040
And the bottom line
is it kills something

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:45.980
like 30,000 people
in an average year.

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:51.230
So this is a serious disease,
more than half a million

00:04:51.230 --> 00:04:53.240
worldwide usually each year.

00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:56.450
And if you tally those
up, every year in the US,

00:04:56.450 --> 00:05:00.320
people's lives are
cut short by a total

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:03.590
of more than 600,000 years.

